<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CERONE, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press.Mackintosh 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
'Miss Saigon' Seeks Broadway Home: The London musical "Miss Saigon" is expected 
to be the next big blockbuster on Broadway, but it may not get there until the 
spring of 1991 or later. The show, a modern "Madama Butterfly" that tells the 
story of the last days of American involvement in the Vietnam War, was supposed 
to get to New York this fall. 
</P>
<P>
Following the smash success of his "Phantom of the Opera," producer Cameron 
Mackintosh is having trouble finding a theater big enough to house his next 
grand production, which includes a 40-member cast and a dramatic helicopter 
landing scene. Mackintosh refuses to take any shortcuts. "I'm not going to put 
'Miss Saigon' on in New York in any less of a way than it is appearing in 
London," he said. The show is estimated to cost $9 million, which would make it 
the most expensive in Broadway history. 
</P>
