<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGEST: WHITTIER; 
</P>
<P>
TANNER DECIDES NOT TO SEEK MONTOYA'S SENATE JOB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Assemblywoman Sally Tanner (D-Baldwin Park) announced Tuesday that she has 
decided not to run for the seat of Sen. Joseph B. Montoya and will seek 
reelection in the 60th Assembly District this year. 
</P>
<P>
Tanner, elected to the Assembly in 1978, acknowledged that she had considered 
running for the 26th Senate District seat now occupied by the Whittier 
Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
Tanner said in a statement that "to succeed in such an effort would require me 
to devote the next five months to campaigning as a virtual full-time candidate. 
That would have made it impossible for me to continue with my duties as chair 
of the Assembly Environmental Safety and Toxic Materials Committee." 
</P>
<P>
Montoya, whose term is up this year, is on trial in federal court on charges of 
bribery, extortion, racketeering and money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
Assemblyman Charles Calderon (D-Whittier) is expected to be a candidate for 
Montoya's seat. Calderon, who represents the 59th Assembly District, said he 
understands the Montoya case will go to the jury later this month. "I expect 
that I'll have an announcement after the return of the verdict by the jury," he 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
