<HEADLINE>
<P>
SLOAN FOUNDATION TO FUND STUDY ON U.S. COMPETITIVENESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY RIVERA BROOKS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Alfred P. Sloan Foundation will give nearly $3 million to five universities 
to study the problems that U.S. companies have competing in the international 
marketplace, the New York-based foundation was scheduled to announce today. 
</P>
<P>
"Competitiveness is an issue that a lot of people are writing about," said 
David J. Teece, head of UC Berkeley's Consortium on Competitiveness and 
Cooperation, which will manage the $2.97-million grant. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not doing as well as we could, as well as we have historically and as 
well as the leading nations we trade with. 
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. economy is in decline . . . and it's not necessary. If we want to set 
a new course, we can." 
</P>
<P>
Faculty from Berkeley, Stanford, Columbia, Harvard and MIT will participate, 
representing a variety of disciplines, including economics, management and 
engineering. 
</P>
<P>
The study is unusual because it requires extensive cooperation from U.S. 
industry, said Ralph E. Gomory, president of the Sloan Foundation. The chief 
executives of five companies -- General Electric, General Motors, Hewlett 
Packard, IBM and Xerox -- have guaranteed cooperation by their firms, he said. 
</P>
<P>
During the 3-to-5-year study, the corporations will help the consortium decide 
what issues to examine, will provide data and will give "a perspective from 
people actually involved in competition on a global basis," Teece said. 
</P>
<P>
"You can't deal with competitiveness in a quick and ad hoc fashion," Gomory 
said. "Scholarship without contact with reality isn't very useful." 
</P>
<P>
The grant is the Sloan Foundation's largest to a university in 25 years. The 
private foundation is a major funding source for college and university 
research in science, economics, engineering, public policy and management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
