<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: SISTER CITIES FUNDS SPENT PROPERLY, 
AUDITORS FIND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than $55,000 in public funds granted to a Sister Cities program overseen 
by Juanita St. John were properly spent, despite some contract and accounting 
irregularities, Los Angeles city auditors said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
The money, approved by the City Council under two contracts, was intended to 
help fund a July, 1986, international conference of city representatives at 
Universal City, according to an audit released by City Controller Rick Tuttle. 
</P>
<P>
The audit was ordered in part because St. John, a business associate of Mayor 
Tom Bradley, is the focus of a criminal probe of possible misuse of funds in an 
Africa trade task force. Auditors found the city's contract with the Sister 
Cities group was vague, poorly monitored by the city clerk and some provisions 
were violated, but that the money was appropriately expended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
